Initialize a Repository: Create a new project folder and use git init to start tracking it.
README & Learning Goals: Create a README.md file to document your project's purpose and your specific learning objectives.
Conventional Commits: Practice making "atomic" commits (one logical change at a time). Follow the Conventional Commits format (e.g., feat: add login logic or docs: update README) to keep history readable.
Branch Management: Use git checkout -b <branch-name> to create new branches for specific features or experiments, keeping your main branch stable. 
